  # Pomofocus Alternative: 5 Better Apps for Serious Focus in 2026

  Pomofocus is a clean, simple Pomodoro timer — and for a quick single session, it's excellent. But if you want to build a sustainable focus habit over weeks and months, Pomofocus has a fundamental problem: **it doesn't save anything.**

  Every time you close the browser, your session data disappears. There's no history, no streak, no analytics. You can't answer "how much did I focus last week?" or "is my focus time increasing?" The tool is a timer, not a habit system.

  This article covers the best Pomofocus alternatives for users who've outgrown single-session timers.

  ---

  ## What Pomofocus Does Well

  Before dismissing it: Pomofocus is genuinely good at what it's designed for.

  - **Instant start** — no login, no setup, just a timer
  - **Clean interface** — no distracting UI elements
  - **Customizable intervals** — work, short break, and long break durations are all adjustable
  - **Task list** — you can add tasks and check them off during a session
  - **Free** — no paywalls, no upsells

  If you're a student who needs a timer for a single study session and doesn't care about long-term tracking, Pomofocus is a solid choice.

  ---

  ## Why Users Look for Alternatives

  The core limitation: **zero persistence.** Pomofocus stores nothing beyond the current browser session. No session history, no daily totals, no streaks, no cross-device sync.

  Secondary limitations:
  - No activity tagging (you can't categorize what type of work you're doing)
  - No analytics dashboard
  - No streak system
  - No way to export or review your data
  - Mobile experience is suboptimal

  ---

  ## The 5 Best Pomofocus Alternatives

  ### 1. Focus Clock — Best Overall (Free)

  **[focusclock.app](https://focusclock.app)** | Free | Browser

  Focus Clock is the most direct upgrade from Pomofocus. It adds everything Pomofocus lacks while keeping a clean, distraction-free interface.

  | Feature | Pomofocus | Focus Clock |
  |---|---|---|
  | Session history | ✗ | ✓ Full history |
  | Heatmap analytics | ✗ | ✓ |
  | Streak counter | ✗ | ✓ |
  | Activity tagging | ✗ | ✓ |
  | Cross-device sync | ✗ | ✓ (with account) |
  | Custom intervals | ✓ | ✓ |
  | Analog clock UI | ✗ | ✓ |
  | Free | ✓ | ✓ |

  The analog clock interface is the most distinctive feature — instead of a digital countdown, you see an arc on a clock face shrinking toward zero. This gives you an immediate spatial sense of time remaining without needing to read numbers.

  **Best for:** Users building a long-term focus habit who want analytics and history.

  ---

  ### 2. Toggl Track — Best for Billable Hours

  **toggl.com/track** | Free / $10/mo | All platforms

  Toggl Track is a professional time-tracking tool with Pomodoro-style timer support. Its analytics are powerful and its reporting features are significantly more detailed than any Pomodoro-specific app. The free tier includes unlimited time tracking, projects, and reports.

  The tradeoff: Toggl is designed for professional time tracking, not focus habit building. The interface reflects this — it's optimized for logging work entries rather than maintaining focused sessions. Starting a "Pomodoro" in Toggl requires more steps than in a dedicated focus app.

  **Best for:** Freelancers billing clients, teams tracking project time.

  ---

  ### 3. Be Focused — Best Native Mac App

  **App Store** | $4.99 | Mac / iOS

  Be Focused is the most polished native Mac/iOS Pomodoro app. It lives in the menu bar, integrates with Reminders, and has a clean session history with basic analytics. The iOS version syncs via iCloud.

  **Best for:** Mac users who prefer native apps and don't want a browser tab open.

  **Limitation:** Mac/iOS only, paid, no web version.

  ---

  ### 4. Focusmate — Best for Accountability

  **focusmate.com** | Free (3 sessions/week) / $6.99/mo | Browser

  Focusmate takes a radically different approach: instead of a solo timer, it pairs you with another person over video for a 50-minute co-working session. You each state your goal at the start and check in at the end. The social accountability dramatically reduces the chance of abandoning the session.

  **Best for:** People who struggle with self-directed focus and benefit from external accountability.

  **Limitation:** Requires video and scheduling, doesn't work well for quick unplanned sessions.

  ---

  ### 5. Session — Best for Deep Work Blocks

  **stayinsession.com** | $4.99/mo | Mac / iOS

  Session is a focused work app for Mac and iOS that combines Pomodoro timing with website blocking, session journaling, and app-level focus modes. It's designed for longer deep work sessions rather than pure Pomodoro cycling.

  **Best for:** Mac users who want website blocking built in and prefer longer sessions.

  **Limitation:** Paid, Mac/iOS only, subscription required for full features.

  ---

  ## Which Alternative Is Right for You?

  | If you want... | Best choice |
  |---|---|
  | Full analytics + free | Focus Clock |
  | Billable hours tracking | Toggl Track |
  | Native Mac/iOS app | Be Focused |
  | Social accountability | Focusmate |
  | Website blocking on Mac | Session |
  | The simplest timer (no history) | Pomofocus |

  ---

  ## Making the Switch from Pomofocus

  If you're moving to Focus Clock from Pomofocus:

  1. Go to [focusclock.app](https://focusclock.app) — no download or account required to start
  2. Click the clock and drag to set your focus duration (same as Pomofocus, just analog)
  3. Create an account to enable session history and cross-device sync (optional for the first session)
  4. After your first session, check the History panel — your session will be logged automatically

  The interface shift from digital numbers (Pomofocus) to an analog arc (Focus Clock) takes about 30 seconds to adjust to.

